Removing as indicated in the comments the secondary interval bounds and adding a normalization stage to have the value at the lower bound non-positive results in the code

```python
f_a = A*lower_bound**3 + B*lower_bound**2 + C*lower_bound + D # Plugs the lower bound into the cubic polynomial
f_b = A*upper_bound**3 + B*upper_bound**2 + C*upper_bound + D # Plugs the upper bound into the cubic polynomial
TOL = 10**-6 # The tolerance

if f_a &gt; 0: A,B,C,D, f_a, f_b = -A,-B,-C,-D, -f_a, -f_b

if f_b &gt; 0 and (f_a and f_b)!=0: # If the equation is increasing from left to right crossing zero and if the bounds aren&#39;t already zeros
    while abs(upper_bound - lower_bound) &gt; TOL: # While the length of the interval is greater than the tolerance, 
        new_mid = 0.5*(upper_bound + lower_bound) # Split the bounds into 2, new_mid is the one of the new bounds
        y_mid = A*new_mid**3 + B*new_mid**2 + C*new_mid + D # Finds the y value for the new_mid value
        
        if y_mid &lt; 0: # If the y value found is negative, perform the next operations
            lower_bound = new_mid # Replaces the lower bound with the new one, which was found when splitting the bounds
                
        if y_mid &gt; 0:
            upper_bound = new_mid
    print( lower_bound, upper_bound )
else: # treat the cases excluded at the start
    if f_b &lt; 0: 
        print( &quot;No sign variation detected in initial interval&quot; )
    else: 
        print( lower_bound if f_a==0 else upper_bound )
```

